CFO Journal.




Luca Maestri’s Route To Apple CFO

















By

Emily Chasan


Emily Chasan
The Wall Street Journal
BiographyEmily Chasan
@echasan
Google+
emily.chasan@wsj.com




                        Mar 4, 2014 6:22 pm  ET
                       


                          
                          0 COMMENTS







Reuters
Luca Maestri, incoming CFO of Apple


When Luca Maestri left his chief financial officer job at Xerox in 2013 to be controller at Apple Inc. it could have been a risky move. C-level executives rarely want to move down the corporate totem pole. But with Tuesday’s news that Mr. Maestri will replace long-time Apple CFO Peter Oppenheimer, the bet has paid off.
Mr. Maestri’s route to CFO of the world’s most valuable company took several turns, including more than seven international assignments and several stints in the CFO chair at some of the world’s biggest companies.
After working his way up through General Motors over 20 years, Mr. Maestri left the carmaker as CFO of its European operations. He headed straight for the C-suite of technology firms with complex manufacturing operations, including CFO of Nokia Siemens Networks and then Xerox.
“I knew they were grooming him [at  Apple],” said Nick Cyprus, the former controller at General Motors who worked with Mr. Maestri.
Mr. Maestri’s former colleagues describe the Italian-born executive as collegial and bright, a supportive manager with a deep understanding of business operations.
Mr. Cyprus said he first met Mr. Maestri when he joined the company and worked on a project to overhaul the company’s accounting functions.
“We needed to make change fast and Luca was more of an asset than a liability,” Mr. Cyprus said.
When Mr. Cyprus asked Mr. Maestri to make changes in the Europe division, he says, “Luca turned around and said if that’s what you need to be successful, I’m behind you.”
In GM’s Europe operation, Mr. Maestri oversaw some difficult issues during the financial crisis as the company hurtled toward a major restructuring. There were tense union negotiations and the overhaul of a complex strategy to boost sales in Europe.
“He was one of the guys who had been around for a while and worked his way up,” Mr. Cyprus said. “He’s really good to work for. He gets controls. He gets infrastructure. He’s a team player.
Mr. Maestri was at Xerox less than two years, but he made an impression by helping the printer and copier company expand into business services.
“One of his big strengths was that he listened,” said Gary Kabureck, a former chief accounting officer at Xerox. “He wanted to understand, and he listened and asked questions until he did understand.”
Xerox, had been looking for a CFO, with extensive international experience to replace long-time CFO Larry Zimmerman. Mr. Maestri fit the bill, having spent a number of years working outside the United States. Mr. Kabureck recalled overhearing him speak on the phone with colleagues in Brazil in clear Portuguese.
“He absolutely understood business processes, from supply chain to currency, and he brought a lot to the table,” Mr. Kabureck said. “He was a good find for Xerox, and a loss when he left.”
Write to Emily Chasan at emily.chasan@wsj.com.




